00:00:30.707 --> 00:00:31.790
ALEXIS BATEMAN: All right.

00:00:31.790 --> 00:00:35.000
So today we're going to do
multi-stakeholder engagement.

00:00:35.000 --> 00:00:37.280
This is a little bit
different than what

00:00:37.280 --> 00:00:38.910
we've been talking
about, as opposed

00:00:38.910 --> 00:00:41.400
to assessing the impacts
of the supply chain

00:00:41.400 --> 00:00:43.450
and looking at where
environmental savings can

00:00:43.450 --> 00:00:43.950
be made.

00:00:43.950 --> 00:00:48.920
It's who can collaborate
to make those changes.

00:00:48.920 --> 00:00:51.729
When a company is trying to
integrate different programs

00:00:51.729 --> 00:00:53.270
within their supply
chain, often they

00:00:53.270 --> 00:00:54.811
can't do it their
own because they're

00:00:54.811 --> 00:00:57.487
working with supply
chain tiers deep--

00:00:57.487 --> 00:00:59.320
further than tier one,
tier two, tier three.

00:00:59.320 --> 00:01:01.653
So they need some different
eyes and different expertise

00:01:01.653 --> 00:01:05.170
that can support their
additional effort.

00:01:05.170 --> 00:01:07.580
Palm oil is a really
excellent case of this

00:01:07.580 --> 00:01:10.470
because it's really deep in
a lot of different companies'

00:01:10.470 --> 00:01:11.120
supply chains.

00:01:11.120 --> 00:01:14.110
It's usually a very small
component of a product

00:01:14.110 --> 00:01:16.780
that they might sell, like in
the case of Nestle's Kit Kat.

00:01:16.780 --> 00:01:22.470
So who, before reading this case
knew about the palm oil issue?

00:01:22.470 --> 00:01:24.446
What do you know about
it, that it was--

00:01:24.446 --> 00:01:25.874
AUDIENCE: Not the best choice.

00:01:25.874 --> 00:01:27.540
ALEXIS BATEMAN: Not
the best choice, OK.

00:01:27.540 --> 00:01:29.740
Did you know about the
environmental impact of it,

00:01:29.740 --> 00:01:33.207
or more just that it
was a bad ingredient?

00:01:33.207 --> 00:01:34.290
AUDIENCE: Bad ingredient--

00:01:34.290 --> 00:01:35.176
ALEXIS BATEMAN: Ingredient, OK.

00:01:35.176 --> 00:01:35.970
AUDIENCE: Nothing specific.

00:01:35.970 --> 00:01:37.180
ALEXIS BATEMAN: Anybody
else have-- yeah,

00:01:37.180 --> 00:01:38.607
what did you know about it?

00:01:38.607 --> 00:01:40.982
AUDIENCE: I knew somewhat
about the environmental impact,

00:01:40.982 --> 00:01:43.090
but yeah, not--

00:01:43.090 --> 00:01:46.376
ALEXIS BATEMAN: Just knowledge
that it was not very good.

00:01:46.376 --> 00:01:48.250
AUDIENCE: Doing research
for the CDP project,

00:01:48.250 --> 00:01:49.871
they talked about the RSPO.

00:01:49.871 --> 00:01:52.920
That's one of the things
they-- my company highlighted

00:01:52.920 --> 00:01:56.543
in their CSR, it's like,
we are 100% certified palm

00:01:56.543 --> 00:01:59.791
oil or whatever, and I was like,
what is certified palm oil?

00:01:59.791 --> 00:02:01.540
ALEXIS BATEMAN: Did
that cause you to look

00:02:01.540 --> 00:02:02.700
into it a little bit more?

00:02:02.700 --> 00:02:03.640
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:02:03.640 --> 00:02:04.515
ALEXIS BATEMAN: Yeah.

00:02:04.515 --> 00:02:07.890
So palm oil is a perfect
example of a material that

00:02:07.890 --> 00:02:09.889
has a lot of
different stakeholders

00:02:09.889 --> 00:02:13.130
that are being affected by
the growing of palm oil,

00:02:13.130 --> 00:02:17.250
by who's sourcing it, and the
supply chain that's in between.

00:02:17.250 --> 00:02:19.276
They have the growers,
they have the mill

00:02:19.276 --> 00:02:20.900
that they process it
in, then they also

00:02:20.900 --> 00:02:21.900
have a lot of middleman.

00:02:21.900 --> 00:02:25.180
So that is where the
supply chain, because it's

00:02:25.180 --> 00:02:27.360
a commodity, a lot of
times the supply chains

00:02:27.360 --> 00:02:29.410
are very non-clear,
not transparent.

00:02:29.410 --> 00:02:30.830
So they're not
able to see what's

00:02:30.830 --> 00:02:34.040
happening deep in their supply
chains, the actual practices.

00:02:34.040 --> 00:02:36.360
Did everyone watching
the Nestle video?

00:02:36.360 --> 00:02:40.420
Because I feel like that was the
linchpin of this whole story,

00:02:40.420 --> 00:02:42.417
where-- did everyone see it?

00:02:42.417 --> 00:02:43.250
You guys all saw it?

00:02:43.250 --> 00:02:44.880
Yeah, so that's
kind of where it all

00:02:44.880 --> 00:02:47.220
began, where
Greenpeace decided--

00:02:47.220 --> 00:02:50.290
they had been actually
looking at the palm oil

00:02:50.290 --> 00:02:52.710
issue for quite a
while before they

00:02:52.710 --> 00:02:54.000
actually when after Nestle.

00:02:54.000 --> 00:02:55.810
And that was a
big turning point,

00:02:55.810 --> 00:02:58.602
when they decided that they
needed to go after the brand.

00:02:58.602 --> 00:03:00.810
And that's commonly what
we've found in our research,

00:03:00.810 --> 00:03:03.110
is that going after the brand
is the more effective strategy

00:03:03.110 --> 00:03:05.300
than actually going into
the deep tier supplier.

00:03:05.300 --> 00:03:06.876
Because it gets
the publicity, it

00:03:06.876 --> 00:03:08.750
gets consumers pushing
the hand of the brand,

00:03:08.750 --> 00:03:11.461
and then the brand actually
looks into their supply chain.

00:03:11.461 --> 00:03:12.960
So what I thought
we would do today,

00:03:12.960 --> 00:03:16.260
I was originally going to break
you up into bigger groups,

00:03:16.260 --> 00:03:18.600
but since we have-- well,
that's pretty good attendance,

00:03:18.600 --> 00:03:22.590
but what I think I'll do is
match you up in groups of three

00:03:22.590 --> 00:03:25.170
and you can talk about
the plan that you created.

00:03:25.170 --> 00:03:31.360
Everyone had the assignment of
acting as a consultant for GAR,

00:03:31.360 --> 00:03:33.370
for Golden Aggregate Resources.

00:03:33.370 --> 00:03:36.820
And I want to see what the
differences were in your plans

00:03:36.820 --> 00:03:40.264
and come to an understanding
of what you guys thought.

00:03:40.264 --> 00:03:41.930
And then we can go
through the questions

00:03:41.930 --> 00:03:44.390
together and see how
you guys went about it.

00:03:44.390 --> 00:03:47.480
So why don't we--
you guys, three,

00:03:47.480 --> 00:03:49.390
why don't we do
threes right here,

00:03:49.390 --> 00:03:52.760
and then three right here,
you guys both triangular,

00:03:52.760 --> 00:03:56.886
three right here, and then
you two, and then back there,

00:03:56.886 --> 00:03:58.010
and then three in the back.

00:03:58.010 --> 00:04:02.040
So we'll spend about 15 minutes,
and you guys just get your plan

00:04:02.040 --> 00:04:04.910
and talk about the
differences you saw.

00:04:04.910 --> 00:04:07.680
And then I'll be spot calling
on answering questions

00:04:07.680 --> 00:04:10.425
and your group will have to
answer on how you look at it.

00:04:14.070 --> 00:04:17.358
So were you guys' strategies
very similar or different?

00:04:17.358 --> 00:04:18.649
AUDIENCE: Completely different.

00:04:18.649 --> 00:04:19.390
ALEXIS BATEMAN:
Completely different.

00:04:19.390 --> 00:04:20.632
In what way?

00:04:20.632 --> 00:04:23.913
AUDIENCE: I said we go with the
complete Greenpeace approach

00:04:23.913 --> 00:04:26.210
and point fingers
at anyone who's not,

00:04:26.210 --> 00:04:29.364
and run our marketing
campaign that way.

00:04:29.364 --> 00:04:31.530
And then Matt took the
completely different approach

00:04:31.530 --> 00:04:33.821
that we should put Greenpeace
as an irrelevant outsider

00:04:33.821 --> 00:04:37.359
and not let the outsiders
run the industry, etc.

00:04:37.359 --> 00:04:39.150
ALEXIS BATEMAN: So what
was-- why would you

00:04:39.150 --> 00:04:41.060
look at it that way?

00:04:41.060 --> 00:04:47.060
AUDIENCE: Just so that if,
particularly from the marketing

00:04:47.060 --> 00:04:49.380
standpoint I wrote
about, from regulation,

00:04:49.380 --> 00:04:52.780
so regulation is going
to be an unknown.

00:04:52.780 --> 00:04:57.380
And you want to establish,
since the RSPO is the industry

00:04:57.380 --> 00:04:59.810
and that represents the
self regulating body,

00:04:59.810 --> 00:05:03.300
if you can establish
yourself as self regulating,

00:05:03.300 --> 00:05:06.250
then you increase the
chances that you will not

00:05:06.250 --> 00:05:08.210
require external help.

00:05:08.210 --> 00:05:09.970
So hopefully the
Indonesian government

00:05:09.970 --> 00:05:12.360
would play a hands
off role if they

00:05:12.360 --> 00:05:14.150
thought you were
taking care of things,

00:05:14.150 --> 00:05:17.640
and then you can be the
master of your own destiny.

00:05:17.640 --> 00:05:19.290
And then from an
investor's side,

00:05:19.290 --> 00:05:22.160
so that it doesn't look like
you're getting pushed around

00:05:22.160 --> 00:05:24.720
and responding in a
reactionary way to everything

00:05:24.720 --> 00:05:28.210
that any external organization
says so that there's

00:05:28.210 --> 00:05:29.955
some confidence
for the investors

00:05:29.955 --> 00:05:31.830
that you're not going
to change your business

00:05:31.830 --> 00:05:34.460
strategy the next time someone
else comes around and says,

00:05:34.460 --> 00:05:35.690
we think you should do this.

00:05:35.690 --> 00:05:36.010
ALEXIS BATEMAN: Sure.

00:05:36.010 --> 00:05:37.890
So we have the
pro-Greenpeace, and then we

00:05:37.890 --> 00:05:40.260
had the non-Greenpeace.

00:05:40.260 --> 00:05:43.408
Any hybrid perspectives?

00:05:43.408 --> 00:05:45.658
All right, we'll get another
team that haven't spoken.

00:05:45.658 --> 00:05:47.630
AUDIENCE: Yeah, I think I might
have missed a couple of things

00:05:47.630 --> 00:05:50.510
in that case study, but I really
took a market driven approach

00:05:50.510 --> 00:05:54.580
to take some of these standards,
organizations they belong to

00:05:54.580 --> 00:05:58.610
and set those as the low bar
and offer an even higher premium

00:05:58.610 --> 00:06:01.560
product that meets the
Greenpeace requirements

00:06:01.560 --> 00:06:03.880
and allow the market to
decide the best [INAUDIBLE].

00:06:03.880 --> 00:06:06.466
And use that additional
revenue to drive change down

00:06:06.466 --> 00:06:08.297
to the farmer and
government level.

00:06:08.297 --> 00:06:10.880
ALEXIS BATEMAN: OK, so we've got
three different perspectives.

00:06:10.880 --> 00:06:14.520
So why don't we diagram out
who everyone's involved,

00:06:14.520 --> 00:06:16.520
and we can see what
everyone else was

00:06:16.520 --> 00:06:19.660
thinking on who was involved.

00:06:19.660 --> 00:06:25.657
Who are all the
stakeholders in this issue?

00:06:25.657 --> 00:06:26.240
AUDIENCE: GAR.

00:06:26.240 --> 00:06:28.890
ALEXIS BATEMAN: GAR, so we've
got, they're at the center,

00:06:28.890 --> 00:06:31.788
the supplier of palm oil.

00:06:31.788 --> 00:06:32.954
AUDIENCE: Rural communities?

00:06:32.954 --> 00:06:35.290
AUDIENCE: Customers,
the direct customers.

00:06:35.290 --> 00:06:36.930
ALEXIS BATEMAN:
Sure, there are--

00:06:36.930 --> 00:06:40.110
so there's several customers.

00:06:40.110 --> 00:06:41.870
AUDIENCE: I mean the
major corporations.

00:06:41.870 --> 00:06:43.932
ALEXIS BATEMAN: Major
corporations, the Nestles

00:06:43.932 --> 00:06:44.890
and Unilevers and such.

00:06:44.890 --> 00:06:46.354
AUDIENCE: Yeah, I
guess that would

00:06:46.354 --> 00:06:48.800
be the [INAUDIBLE] brands.

00:06:48.800 --> 00:06:51.090
ALEXIS BATEMAN: So
they're out here.

00:06:51.090 --> 00:06:53.610
They're a little bit separated.

00:06:53.610 --> 00:06:54.356
Who else?

00:06:54.356 --> 00:06:55.272
AUDIENCE: The farmers.

00:06:55.272 --> 00:06:56.855
ALEXIS BATEMAN: We've
got the farmers.

00:06:56.855 --> 00:07:02.085
So they're in between
GAR and the corporation.

00:07:07.250 --> 00:07:08.660
AUDIENCE: Indonesian government.

00:07:08.660 --> 00:07:09.750
ALEXIS BATEMAN:
Indonesian government.

00:07:09.750 --> 00:07:10.750
Where would we put them?

00:07:10.750 --> 00:07:14.520
They're kind of
out in left field.

00:07:14.520 --> 00:07:19.355
Oh, we're going to test
my spelling skills.

00:07:23.155 --> 00:07:26.970
AUDIENCE: Don't we
see the processing

00:07:26.970 --> 00:07:29.132
mills are an intermediary?

00:07:29.132 --> 00:07:31.855
ALEXIS BATEMAN: Yeah, so there's
the mills and processing.

00:07:41.626 --> 00:07:43.108
AUDIENCE: The certifying bodies.

00:07:43.108 --> 00:07:44.774
ALEXIS BATEMAN:
Certifying bodies, yeah.

00:07:54.987 --> 00:07:56.820
AUDIENCE: I would say
above the corporations

00:07:56.820 --> 00:07:58.115
you have the consumers.

00:07:58.115 --> 00:07:59.156
ALEXIS BATEMAN: Oh, yeah.

00:08:09.299 --> 00:08:11.714
Anybody else?

00:08:11.714 --> 00:08:13.230
AUDIENCE: Environmental
ag agencies.

00:08:13.230 --> 00:08:13.660
ALEXIS BATEMAN: Sure.

00:08:13.660 --> 00:08:14.862
Where should we put them?

00:08:14.862 --> 00:08:15.570
They're kind of--

00:08:15.570 --> 00:08:18.230
AUDIENCE: There's the
environmental engineer type

00:08:18.230 --> 00:08:19.896
people, and then
there's just people

00:08:19.896 --> 00:08:21.230
who care about the environment.

00:08:21.230 --> 00:08:22.396
ALEXIS BATEMAN: That's true.

00:08:26.230 --> 00:08:28.730
AUDIENCE: And investors.

00:08:28.730 --> 00:08:30.840
ALEXIS BATEMAN:
Investors, absolutely.

00:08:30.840 --> 00:08:33.770
So they are kind of in between.

00:08:38.670 --> 00:08:41.385
And we have green customers.

00:08:52.010 --> 00:08:54.384
So you have anyone else?

00:08:54.384 --> 00:08:55.550
AUDIENCE: Local communities.

00:08:55.550 --> 00:08:57.466
ALEXIS BATEMAN: Local
communities, absolutely.

00:08:57.466 --> 00:08:59.650
So they're down here
with the farmers.

00:09:08.280 --> 00:09:10.927
What about the people who
are impacted by the burning?

00:09:10.927 --> 00:09:12.260
So it is actually the community.

00:09:12.260 --> 00:09:13.840
Well, that would be also
local communities, but also

00:09:13.840 --> 00:09:14.923
international communities.

00:09:14.923 --> 00:09:17.884
I actually lived in Singapore
when they had the burnings,

00:09:17.884 --> 00:09:19.050
and there was actually haze.

00:09:19.050 --> 00:09:21.062
I was outside playing
soccer and coughed up

00:09:21.062 --> 00:09:22.520
a lung because you
could actually--

00:09:22.520 --> 00:09:25.110
the haze was so thick.

00:09:25.110 --> 00:09:26.282
It's not a fake thing.

00:09:26.282 --> 00:09:27.740
We've got international
communities

00:09:27.740 --> 00:09:31.455
as well that were impacted
by slash-and-burn practices.

00:09:39.095 --> 00:09:42.530
So you have all
these stakeholders

00:09:42.530 --> 00:09:45.150
and GAR is trying to
figure out their strategy.

00:09:45.150 --> 00:09:47.670
So you think about who
Greenpeace went to.

00:09:47.670 --> 00:09:50.250
They went directly
to the corporation

00:09:50.250 --> 00:09:52.550
and attacked their strategy
and what they were doing,

00:09:52.550 --> 00:09:54.466
their actual material
that they were sourcing.

00:09:54.466 --> 00:09:56.220
But then that got
translated back

00:09:56.220 --> 00:09:59.942
to the actual company that
was dealing with the palm oil.

00:09:59.942 --> 00:10:01.650
And then they had to
go through all these

00:10:01.650 --> 00:10:04.940
different-- so did everyone
think about these as they were

00:10:04.940 --> 00:10:07.860
going through their strategy?

00:10:07.860 --> 00:10:08.760
Yes?

00:10:08.760 --> 00:10:09.460
Sort of?

00:10:09.460 --> 00:10:09.960
Not really?

00:10:09.960 --> 00:10:11.590
No, you guys seem to
decide fairly quickly.

00:10:11.590 --> 00:10:12.100
Anyone else?

00:10:12.100 --> 00:10:14.370
Did anyone else not
account for one of these

00:10:14.370 --> 00:10:16.780
and might think differently,
think about some

00:10:16.780 --> 00:10:21.181
of these other
external stakeholders?

00:10:21.181 --> 00:10:21.680
No?

00:10:21.680 --> 00:10:22.140
All right.

00:10:22.140 --> 00:10:23.620
So everyone thought
about everyone.

00:10:23.620 --> 00:10:24.080
Everyone's good.

00:10:24.080 --> 00:10:24.830
AUDIENCE: I forgot
about the mills.

00:10:24.830 --> 00:10:25.656
ALEXIS BATEMAN: The mills?

00:10:25.656 --> 00:10:26.156
Yeah.

00:10:26.156 --> 00:10:27.128
The mills and press.

00:10:27.128 --> 00:10:29.128
AUDIENCE: I was thinking
about the other growers

00:10:29.128 --> 00:10:31.856
and other competitors
who are joining the ISPO

00:10:31.856 --> 00:10:33.784
and who might also [INAUDIBLE].

00:10:33.784 --> 00:10:35.950
ALEXIS BATEMAN: The other--
I'm sorry, say it again.

00:10:35.950 --> 00:10:36.780
AUDIENCE: Other growers
and competitors.

00:10:36.780 --> 00:10:37.780
ALEXIS BATEMAN: Oh, yes.

00:10:37.780 --> 00:10:39.637
The other companies
that are-- so there

00:10:39.637 --> 00:10:43.710
are also the other
palm oil companies.

00:10:46.520 --> 00:10:49.460
So they're also
kind of in between.

00:10:49.460 --> 00:10:51.270
No, they'd probably
be over here.

00:10:51.270 --> 00:10:53.416
You get the picture.

00:10:53.416 --> 00:10:55.290
Anyone want to talk
about their strategy that

00:10:55.290 --> 00:10:57.600
are different from these
three, that they thought--

00:10:57.600 --> 00:10:59.140
the marketing strategy?

00:10:59.140 --> 00:11:01.350
Let's start with
the first question

00:11:01.350 --> 00:11:03.950
in terms of how you're going
to market your palm oil.

00:11:03.950 --> 00:11:07.870
Given the strategy they have
now, how would you go about it?

00:11:07.870 --> 00:11:10.360
AUDIENCE: We thought--
we agreed that we'd

00:11:10.360 --> 00:11:13.900
be more vocal about
publishing the fact

00:11:13.900 --> 00:11:16.000
that we were trying
to take a leadership

00:11:16.000 --> 00:11:17.010
role in sustainability.

00:11:17.010 --> 00:11:20.060
So one of those
things might include

00:11:20.060 --> 00:11:21.980
having an annual
sustainability report

00:11:21.980 --> 00:11:23.405
or something along those lines.

00:11:23.405 --> 00:11:25.780
And then we talked
about continuing

00:11:25.780 --> 00:11:31.230
to work with Greenpeace to
maybe even set increasingly,

00:11:31.230 --> 00:11:34.357
slightly, higher standards
or goals for ourselves.

00:11:34.357 --> 00:11:36.542
And then again, just
talking about those goals

00:11:36.542 --> 00:11:39.390
and putting those out
there so that it gave us

00:11:39.390 --> 00:11:41.590
additional credibility
in the market

00:11:41.590 --> 00:11:45.707
as a leader in that front.

00:11:45.707 --> 00:11:47.790
ALEXIS BATEMAN: So I don't
know if you guys caught

00:11:47.790 --> 00:11:49.970
the difference between
Greenpeace and the Forest

00:11:49.970 --> 00:11:50.610
Trust.

00:11:50.610 --> 00:11:52.310
Did you guys catch
any subtle difference

00:11:52.310 --> 00:11:54.262
of how each of those NGOs work?

00:11:54.262 --> 00:11:56.220
AUDIENCE: The Forest
Trust kind of-- Greenpeace

00:11:56.220 --> 00:11:58.110
