00:40:09.310 --> 00:40:10.790
the issues behind that.

00:40:10.790 --> 00:40:15.430
There's definitely different
issues in palm oil and ethanol,

00:40:15.430 --> 00:40:18.884
but I'd encourage you to look up
what's happening in the ethanol

00:40:18.884 --> 00:40:20.550
supply chain and
what's happening there,

00:40:20.550 --> 00:40:22.580
but not off the top my head.

00:40:22.580 --> 00:40:26.650
If I find one, though,
I'll send it to you.

00:40:26.650 --> 00:40:30.590
So I thought the palm oil
was a perfect example.

00:40:30.590 --> 00:40:34.600
It's like one of the most-- not
the most, but a very complex

00:40:34.600 --> 00:40:37.370
example of multi-stakeholder
engagement.

00:40:37.370 --> 00:40:43.060
This is just a small perspective
on how many actual stakeholders

00:40:43.060 --> 00:40:43.940
are involved.

00:40:43.940 --> 00:40:45.680
Within each of
those subheadings,

00:40:45.680 --> 00:40:49.900
there's multiple
corporations, multiple mills,

00:40:49.900 --> 00:40:51.210
thousands of farmers.

00:40:51.210 --> 00:40:53.370
And so getting all
these people together

00:40:53.370 --> 00:40:55.140
to agree on different
certifications

00:40:55.140 --> 00:40:57.880
and how they're going
to actually run that

00:40:57.880 --> 00:41:01.210
was incredibly complex, and
it's still very much ongoing.

00:41:01.210 --> 00:41:04.420
There's still a lot of debate,
external debate from the World

00:41:04.420 --> 00:41:05.980
Wildlife Federation
on the standards.

00:41:05.980 --> 00:41:09.780
A lot of different NGOs are
commenting on how it's going.

00:41:09.780 --> 00:41:12.700
So we actually covered--
some of the stories

00:41:12.700 --> 00:41:16.740
that we've looked at and a lot
of the times when companies do

00:41:16.740 --> 00:41:19.250
tend to commit to
multi-stakeholder engagements

00:41:19.250 --> 00:41:21.826
or realize that they have
a gap in their strategy,

00:41:21.826 --> 00:41:23.200
in their sustainability
strategy,

00:41:23.200 --> 00:41:25.360
is when an NGO finds it.

00:41:25.360 --> 00:41:27.840
And so that's sort ot--
these are just two.

00:41:27.840 --> 00:41:30.680
So Nestle and Greenpeace is
what we talked about today,

00:41:30.680 --> 00:41:32.730
where Greenpeace
activists actually

00:41:32.730 --> 00:41:36.410
dropped into their shareholder
meeting dressed as gorillas

00:41:36.410 --> 00:41:38.640
and totally blockaded the doors.

00:41:38.640 --> 00:41:42.270
And there's other
examples of Greenpeace.

00:41:42.270 --> 00:41:45.610
I don't know if they rock
climbed or parachuted

00:41:45.610 --> 00:41:49.770
onto the top of HP and actually
spray painted toxic materials

00:41:49.770 --> 00:41:51.757
on the top of HP because
they're attacking

00:41:51.757 --> 00:41:53.340
HP for some of the
materials that they

00:41:53.340 --> 00:41:57.290
were using in their supply chain
that were labeled as toxic.

00:41:57.290 --> 00:42:00.266
So they have some very
Interesting campaign tactics,

00:42:00.266 --> 00:42:02.140
but definitely get people
to look, especially

00:42:02.140 --> 00:42:04.220
with the Nestle commercial.

00:42:04.220 --> 00:42:05.660
This actually was
a different case

00:42:05.660 --> 00:42:10.180
where the Rainforest
Alliance Network actually

00:42:10.180 --> 00:42:11.230
attacked Mitsubishi.

00:42:11.230 --> 00:42:13.890
So Mitsubishi is actually
three different companies.

00:42:13.890 --> 00:42:15.280
There's a parent
company and then

00:42:15.280 --> 00:42:16.900
there's Mitsubishi
Electric, and then

00:42:16.900 --> 00:42:20.250
there's Mitsubishi Automotive
which is probably what we're

00:42:20.250 --> 00:42:22.440
most familiar with, the cars.

00:42:22.440 --> 00:42:26.670
But actually the parent company
was sourcing paper products

00:42:26.670 --> 00:42:28.490
that were unsustainable,
and there's a lot

00:42:28.490 --> 00:42:30.160
of clear cutting of rainforest.

00:42:30.160 --> 00:42:33.110
And what happened was that they
just don't have a public face,

00:42:33.110 --> 00:42:34.950
so the Rainforest
Alliance Network actually

00:42:34.950 --> 00:42:37.430
decided to attack the
automotive company,

00:42:37.430 --> 00:42:41.291
even though they actually had
no connection to the paper

00:42:41.291 --> 00:42:41.790
sourcing.

00:42:41.790 --> 00:42:45.529
So this is where NGOs are
using different strategies

00:42:45.529 --> 00:42:46.570
to get it into the media.

00:42:46.570 --> 00:42:49.920
So they actually had
sit-ins at the dealerships.

00:42:49.920 --> 00:42:52.490
And what happened was the
dealerships then called

00:42:52.490 --> 00:42:54.220
Mitsubishi Automotive
Electric and said,

00:42:54.220 --> 00:42:55.890
we can't deal with this,
we're losing sales.

00:42:55.890 --> 00:42:57.400
And then the
Mitsubishi executives

00:42:57.400 --> 00:42:59.025
across three different
parent companies

00:42:59.025 --> 00:43:01.950
had to actually decide
what they were going to do.

00:43:01.950 --> 00:43:05.100
The sad story is that the
electric and the automotive

00:43:05.100 --> 00:43:08.021
actually committed to
paper sourcing policies

00:43:08.021 --> 00:43:09.520
and the parent
company still didn't,

00:43:09.520 --> 00:43:11.936
because they couldn't get down
to the actual root problem.

00:43:11.936 --> 00:43:13.580
So that's some of
the perspective

00:43:13.580 --> 00:43:17.220
on how NGOs go about getting
into these complex problems

00:43:17.220 --> 00:43:19.755
by pushing the hand of
the public brand owners.

00:43:23.770 --> 00:43:27.140
So one of the most
clear, simple ways

00:43:27.140 --> 00:43:29.450
that companies are
engaging is when

00:43:29.450 --> 00:43:33.490
they realize that they
need help in increasing

00:43:33.490 --> 00:43:35.070
their sustainability.

00:43:35.070 --> 00:43:38.500
Chiquita actually
has-- I think they

00:43:38.500 --> 00:43:43.890
started in 1992 with the
Rainforest Alliance Network.

00:43:43.890 --> 00:43:47.610
They were getting
training and information

00:43:47.610 --> 00:43:51.630
on how to grow their
bananas more sustainably,

00:43:51.630 --> 00:43:54.730
so they're using the RAN to work
with their farmers and growers.

00:43:54.730 --> 00:43:58.190
And so they've actually
used them for over 20 years.

00:43:58.190 --> 00:43:59.805
Chiquita has sort
of a checkered past,

00:43:59.805 --> 00:44:03.634
so they obviously decided
they needed to have a partner.

00:44:03.634 --> 00:44:06.050
That was a one-on-one partner,
and they've actually worked

00:44:06.050 --> 00:44:08.910
with them for many years
to look at organic issues

00:44:08.910 --> 00:44:12.430
and Sustainable transportation
their products and all

00:44:12.430 --> 00:44:13.690
of the above.

00:44:13.690 --> 00:44:17.160
And actually, Chiquita
sought out Tony Craig

00:44:17.160 --> 00:44:19.490
to do their carbon
footprint, so they obviously

00:44:19.490 --> 00:44:20.650
need a lot of help.

00:44:20.650 --> 00:44:23.990
They were actually
looking to Tony

00:44:23.990 --> 00:44:27.260
to assess their entire carbon
footprint of a single banana.

00:44:27.260 --> 00:44:29.270
So we'd talked
about that earlier.

00:44:29.270 --> 00:44:32.225
Other one-on-one
partnerships-- Dell-- who

00:44:32.225 --> 00:44:33.581
has a Dell computer in here?

00:44:33.581 --> 00:44:34.080
Anybody?

00:44:34.080 --> 00:44:37.360
So a pretty big brand.

00:44:37.360 --> 00:44:40.000
They've actually-- one
of their major problems

00:44:40.000 --> 00:44:42.530
that they were attacked
with was their e-waste.

00:44:42.530 --> 00:44:45.979
So what are they doing with
the end of life products?

00:44:45.979 --> 00:44:47.770
Several years ago, when
they were attacked,

00:44:47.770 --> 00:44:49.020
I think it was
about 10 years ago,

00:44:49.020 --> 00:44:50.186
they weren't doing anything.

00:44:50.186 --> 00:44:51.650
And so instead,
now, today they've

00:44:51.650 --> 00:44:54.180
partnered with Goodwill
as a collection point.

00:44:54.180 --> 00:44:58.732
So the Goodwill can actually
collect Dell products,

00:44:58.732 --> 00:45:00.440
and they also collect
any other products.

00:45:00.440 --> 00:45:01.860
Actually, if you
guys look it up,

00:45:01.860 --> 00:45:03.370
you can turn your
e-waste in there,

00:45:03.370 --> 00:45:05.620
and actually Goodwill
collects those products

00:45:05.620 --> 00:45:09.410
and then Dell pays for the
actual recycling and separation

00:45:09.410 --> 00:45:12.950
of their computers so that
they don't go into landfills.

00:45:12.950 --> 00:45:15.810
These are one-on-one
partnerships

00:45:15.810 --> 00:45:19.240
where the company decided they
needed help with their strategy

00:45:19.240 --> 00:45:21.100
and then they sought
out a partner that

00:45:21.100 --> 00:45:24.160
was a technical expert in that.

00:45:24.160 --> 00:45:27.260
In the case of Walmart and the
Environmental Defense Fund,

00:45:27.260 --> 00:45:30.040
you guys will get a
little bit more insight

00:45:30.040 --> 00:45:32.360
into what they're doing
in their partnership.

00:45:32.360 --> 00:45:37.390
But when Walmart decided to
integrate a sustainability

00:45:37.390 --> 00:45:41.810
program about in 2005, so
almost 10 years ago, they

00:45:41.810 --> 00:45:44.964
needed many partners, and they
need one strategic partner

00:45:44.964 --> 00:45:46.630
to kind of guide their
overall strategy.

00:45:46.630 --> 00:45:48.640
So they brought in
Environmental Defense Fund

00:45:48.640 --> 00:45:50.400
to look at their
overarching strategies

00:45:50.400 --> 00:45:53.020
and how they were going to
drive that into their business.

00:45:53.020 --> 00:45:55.640
So EDF is actually a
really unique story.

00:45:55.640 --> 00:46:00.360
We're hoping to get the woman
that is actually co-located

00:46:00.360 --> 00:46:01.910
with Walmart in Bentonville.

00:46:01.910 --> 00:46:04.900
Their offices are in
Bentonville, Arkansas,

00:46:04.900 --> 00:46:07.359
and obviously Walmart,
being one of the largest

00:46:07.359 --> 00:46:09.400
retailers in the world,
has a significant impact.

00:46:09.400 --> 00:46:12.120
So they actually co-located
their office there so

00:46:12.120 --> 00:46:14.450
that they could have
a person on site

00:46:14.450 --> 00:46:16.810
and work with different
Walmart individuals

00:46:16.810 --> 00:46:18.640
as they come along with
different problems.

00:46:18.640 --> 00:46:23.060
So that's sort of
a unique thing.

00:46:23.060 --> 00:46:25.180
These are examples
of one-on-one,

00:46:25.180 --> 00:46:27.340
where the company
decided they needed help,

00:46:27.340 --> 00:46:29.290
they sought out
a single partner.

00:46:29.290 --> 00:46:32.700
Other cases are
when a company has

00:46:32.700 --> 00:46:35.570
a lot of different partners, and
this is true of many companies

00:46:35.570 --> 00:46:38.360
where they've decided
they needed support

00:46:38.360 --> 00:46:40.090
in different angles.

00:46:40.090 --> 00:46:42.434
Starbucks, a major
coffee company, I'm sure

00:46:42.434 --> 00:46:43.600
you guys don't know of them.

00:46:43.600 --> 00:46:48.660
But they have brought in a
lot of different partners.

00:46:48.660 --> 00:46:52.060
In terms of how they're moving
their cups and other products

00:46:52.060 --> 00:46:56.000
to more recyclable-- and
using more recycled material

00:46:56.000 --> 00:46:57.490
in their actual
products, they've

00:46:57.490 --> 00:47:00.460
[INAUDIBLE] the Sustainable
Packaging Coalition.

00:47:00.460 --> 00:47:03.060
They've had other-- for
more of their social issues,

00:47:03.060 --> 00:47:06.147
looking at helping
their farmers that

00:47:06.147 --> 00:47:07.730
grow their coffee
and their chocolate,

00:47:07.730 --> 00:47:10.610
and they've partnered
with Root Capital.

00:47:10.610 --> 00:47:13.120
In terms of how they're
actually integrating

00:47:13.120 --> 00:47:14.720
recycling into
their sites, which

00:47:14.720 --> 00:47:16.710
has been an ongoing
problem, they've

00:47:16.710 --> 00:47:18.990
had working with the National
Recycling Correlation,

00:47:18.990 --> 00:47:19.950
and so forth.

00:47:19.950 --> 00:47:22.120
So each of these
different angles

00:47:22.120 --> 00:47:25.700
that they've found
a blind spot, they

00:47:25.700 --> 00:47:28.870
sought out a partner so that
they can improve their strategy

00:47:28.870 --> 00:47:31.060
and also have an
expert in that area,

00:47:31.060 --> 00:47:33.440
as opposed to
developing internally.

00:47:33.440 --> 00:47:35.820
In some cases, some
companies choose

00:47:35.820 --> 00:47:37.820
to develop that
expertise internally.

00:47:37.820 --> 00:47:40.280
So they bring in a
sustainability person

00:47:40.280 --> 00:47:42.370
that is an expert in
packaging, and that's

00:47:42.370 --> 00:47:43.600
true of some companies.

00:47:43.600 --> 00:47:45.550
And some decide
that they don't want

00:47:45.550 --> 00:47:47.080
to develop that
internal expertise,

00:47:47.080 --> 00:47:48.580
they'd rather seek
out someone who's

00:47:48.580 --> 00:47:53.242
already a leader in that area.

00:47:53.242 --> 00:47:53.825
Any questions?

00:47:57.690 --> 00:48:01.190
And then the last
kind of major bucket.

00:48:01.190 --> 00:48:02.970
Of course, these
can all be split

00:48:02.970 --> 00:48:04.880
into many different hybrid.

00:48:04.880 --> 00:48:07.800
Some people have a
one-on-one collaboration

00:48:07.800 --> 00:48:09.227
and their industry
collaboration,

00:48:09.227 --> 00:48:11.060
or they have multiple
partners and industry.

00:48:11.060 --> 00:48:13.874
So everyone pretty much
just everything now,

00:48:13.874 --> 00:48:15.040
most of the major companies.

00:48:15.040 --> 00:48:17.730
So the other kind of
example would be an industry

00:48:17.730 --> 00:48:20.070
collaboration, as we talked
about with the RSPO, where

00:48:20.070 --> 00:48:24.240
they bring together
multiple stakeholders.

00:48:24.240 --> 00:48:26.770
They are this
convening a group that

00:48:26.770 --> 00:48:29.050
discusses the major
issues, and then they

00:48:29.050 --> 00:48:32.090
may provide certification,
they may provide training,

00:48:32.090 --> 00:48:35.060
they may provide information for
the company's stakeholders, all

00:48:35.060 --> 00:48:35.610
of the above.

00:48:35.610 --> 00:48:38.260
So that was-- RSPO
is one example.

00:48:38.260 --> 00:48:40.670
Another example is the
Sustainability Consortium.

00:48:40.670 --> 00:48:44.220
Has anyone heard of the
Sustainability Consortium?

00:48:44.220 --> 00:48:49.780
OK, so that's the biggest
one, so it's all downhill

00:48:49.780 --> 00:48:51.720
from there.

00:48:51.720 --> 00:48:54.880
The Sustainability Consortium
actually came out of Walmart.

00:48:54.880 --> 00:48:58.890
So Walmart realized
that they could only

00:48:58.890 --> 00:49:02.194
influence so much in terms
of their environmental impact

00:49:02.194 --> 00:49:03.360
within their own four walls.

00:49:03.360 --> 00:49:06.780
They realized most other impact
was outside their four walls.

00:49:06.780 --> 00:49:10.570
They're buying P&G detergents,
they're buying Unilever shampoo

00:49:10.570 --> 00:49:14.450
and s and they realize all
their suppliers were actually

00:49:14.450 --> 00:49:15.850
a major source of the impact.

00:49:15.850 --> 00:49:17.680
So instead of just
trying to focus

00:49:17.680 --> 00:49:20.590
on their own internal impacts,
they pumped a bunch of money

00:49:20.590 --> 00:49:22.719
into making an
institution where all

00:49:22.719 --> 00:49:24.260
of these different
suppliers, as well

00:49:24.260 --> 00:49:26.870
as other people from
across the industry,

00:49:26.870 --> 00:49:28.490
could come together
and understand

00:49:28.490 --> 00:49:29.980
the impacts of products.

